#
# cup polls the registries hosting every image used by every container
# Docker is currently running.  `cup check` is the one-shot CLI mode:
# enumerate containers via bollard, group by image reference,
# concurrent OCI registry HEAD requests to compare local digest vs
# remote `:latest` (or whatever tag was pulled), produce a formatted
# terminal table.  `cup serve` flips the same logic into long-running
# mode: HTTP server on `--port 8000` shows the same data in a web UI
# rendered via Liquid templates, and tokio-cron-scheduler drives a
# periodic-refresh cycle that updates the cached snapshot + optionally
# pushes a webhook notification (Discord / Slack / Generic POST) when
# new updates are detected.  The configured cron expression
# determines refresh cadence (default every 6 hours).
#
# ============================================================================
# === AXIS 187 OPENS — cron-expression scheduling libraries ===============
# === Rust=242 OPENS at slot 1/0/0 ========================================
# ============================================================================
# Axis position: Rust=242 OPENS Axis 187 at slot 1/0/0 — the first of the
# three lanes for the canonical cron-expression scheduling trio.  The
# axis anchors on a single pure-host-language scheduler library that
# parses classic crontab syntax (`0 0 * * *`) into a recurring trigger
# and dispatches user-supplied callbacks on each fire, with both
# synchronous and async-first variants and (in some implementations)
# persistent job storage:
